text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading issues**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how if the `codeSource` is null, a test might fail. I wonder if using a `try-catch` for errors could help. I shouldn't skip over potential issues. It seems like I might need a custom `ClassLoader`. Perhaps I could create a `ChildFirstSqlClassLoader` that extends `URLClassLoader`. This could load `groovy.sql.Sql` from the same jar as the library while delegating other classes to the parent.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class detection**\\n\\nI'm considering the third request via line 738, where I might need to return the SuccessfulFallbackDriver.class as the parent test class. I'm wondering if Class.forName could be called twice, though. Maybe a safer approach would be to use stack-based detection. I think I could check if the stack contains `java.lang.Class.forName` since the native frame might not be visible. Also, the top stack may include Class.forName. It's tricky, but I think I can sort it out!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating classloading**\\n\\nI need to adapt the classloader to ensure that when line 738 returns `SqlTest.FallbackLoadedDriver.class`, which is already loaded by the parent, it behaves correctly. I’m curious if the `ClassLoader.loadClass` contract allows returning a class loaded by a different loader. From what I understand, it does allow `loadClass` to return any class, so I need to check if `Sql.loadDriver` is properly validating that.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_aUYljDFbjSJhBu2C6caeP90P|fc_029c64c034dc2895016a112f666018819cb7db809a6b2ad9c7", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"URLClassLoader\" -n tests/src | head -30"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 946, "output": 4101, "cacheRead": 28160, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 33207, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "tim